According to the 1961 Vienna Convention, Becker is not bound by legal processes in the courts of any country for so long as he remains a recognised diplomatic agent. PRETORIA – Three-time Wimbledon champion Boris Becker is fighting to claim diplomatic immunity from his ongoing bankruptcy proceedings. Becker declared bankruptcy last year in the hope of clearing his nearly R1 billion worth of debt. But he’s back in the London High Court claiming his appointment as a sporting, cultural and humanitarian affairs attaché for the Central African Republic gives him immunity. According to the 1961 Vienna Convention, Becker is not bound by legal processes in the courts of any country for so long as he remains a recognised diplomatic agent. It means he will only have to pay his debts if the Central African Republic give their consent to debt collectors.